&lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>
    &lt;h3>
        Key facts about the PM² Guide
    &lt;/h3>
&lt;/div>
&lt;p>
    &lt;strong>Who&lt;/strong> has created the PM2 guide?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    This project management standard has been produced and published by the Centre of Excellence in Project Management (CoE
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;
    style='FONT-SIZE: 10.5pt; FONT-FAMILY: &quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif; mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family: PMingLiU; mso-bidi-font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA'>
    PM²),&lt;/span> an entity of the European Commission.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    &lt;strong>What&lt;/strong> does the PM2 guide&amp;nbsp;provide to its users?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    PM2 provides&amp;nbsp;to its users the&amp;nbsp;following:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ol>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            A project governance structure&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Process guidelines&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Artefact templates&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Guidelines for using the artefacts&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            A set of effective mindsets&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;p>
    &lt;strong>When&lt;/strong> was the&amp;nbsp;Open PM2 guide&amp;nbsp;created?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The current edition of the PM2 guide (v 3.0)&amp;nbsp;was published in October 2018.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>Where&lt;/strong> can the PM2 guide be successfully deployed?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    When the Centre of Excellence in Project Management (CoEPM²) of the European Commission created this project management
    standard, its objective was to respond to the needs of European Union institutions and projects but, any institutions
    can also use this guide to effectively manage their projects.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>How&lt;/strong> does the use PM2 guide improve the project success?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    The PM2 guide emphasises among others&amp;nbsp;the importance of close collaboration between two groups, namely,
    the&amp;nbsp;requestor side and the provider side. During the entire project, the requestor side (the Project Owner, the
    Business Manager ane the Business Implementation Group) work hand in hand with the provider side (the Solution
    Provider, the Project Manager and the Project Core team) in order to achieve the project objectives. Also important in
    PM2 are transition and business implementation plans, plans whose execution ensures project deliverables are seemlessly
    integrated in the client's operations.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>How many&lt;/strong> stakeholder categories&amp;nbsp;do we find in a PM2 project?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    Rather than instrumental, projects are &lt;a href=&quot;https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2006.08.006&quot;>sociopolitical
    processes&lt;/a> in which&amp;nbsp;politics and &lt;a
    href=&quot;https://www.crcpress.com/Tools-for-Complex-Projects/Remington-Pollack/p/book/9780566087417&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;>&lt;u>&lt;font color=&quot;#0066cc&quot;>conflicting interests&lt;/font>&lt;/u>&lt;/a> among stakeholders are commonplace, hence
    the importance of adopting&amp;nbsp;a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/8756972818786663&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;>&lt;u>&lt;font color=&quot;#0066cc&quot;>multiple stakeholder perspective&lt;/font>&lt;/u>&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;when
    discussing&amp;nbsp;various concepts such as project objectives and success. PM2 groups project stakeholders into
    the&amp;nbsp;following five (5) categories or layers:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ol>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Business Governing Layer&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Steering Layer&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Directing Layer&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Managing Layer&lt;br />
            &lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Performing Layer&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    In addition to&amp;nbsp;these five&amp;nbsp;regular categories, there is another called Project Support Team
    which&amp;nbsp;comprises a number of optional roles.
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
